solution.p:
Let f(x)=\log x and x_0=10. Then
f(x)&=\log x & f'(x)&=\frac{1}{x} & f''(x)&=-\frac{1}{x^2}
f(10)&=\log 10\approx 2.30259 & f'(10)&=\frac{1}{10} & f''(10)&=-\frac{1}{100}
so that, with x=10.3,
\log 10.3\amp=f(10.3)\approx f(10)+f'(10)(10.3-10) =2.30259+\frac{0.3}{10}
\amp=2.33259
The error in this approximation (excluding the error in the given data \log 10\approx 2.30259) is \dfrac{1}{2} f''(z)(10.3-10)^2 for some z between 10 and 10.3. Because f''(z)=-\dfrac{1}{z^2} increases as z increases, it must be between -\dfrac{1}{10^2} and -\dfrac{1}{10.3^2}. This forces \dfrac{1}{2} f''(z)(10.3-10)^2 to be between -\dfrac{1}{2}\cdot \dfrac{1}{10^2}(0.3)^2=-0.00045 and -\dfrac{1}{2}\cdot \dfrac{1}{10.3^2}(0.3)^2 \lt -0.00042.
